In CSS, there is no way to apply a hover effect on one element to another element within the HTML DOM structure purely using CSS. 

However, you can achieve similar effects using JavaScript or jQuery. With these scripting languages, you can listen for the hover event on one element and apply appropriate styles or trigger actions on another element based on that event.

Here's an example of how you can achieve this effect using jQuery:

HTML:
```html
<div class="hoverable">
  Hover over me!
</div>
<div class="target">
  I will change when the other element is hovered.
</div>
```

CSS:
```css
.target {
  color: green;
}

.target.hovered {
  font-weight: bold;
}
```

JavaScript (jQuery):
```javascript
$(document).ready(function() {
  $('.hoverable').hover(function() {
    $('.target').toggleClass('hovered');
  });
});
```

In the above example, when you hover over the element with the class "hoverable", it triggers the hover function in JavaScript that adds or removes the "hovered" class on the element with the class "target".

By changing the CSS properties of the "hovered" class, you can modify the appearance or behavior of the target element when the hover event occurs on the hoverable element.
